  "summary": "Inspector Sharp interrogates Nigel Chapman, a twenty-five-year-old student of Bronze Age and Medieval History at the University of London who was born in Nagasaki. Nigel denies having any romantic interest in Celia Austin, noting that she disliked his sense of humor, despite the fact that he saw her daily. He recounts that the group last saw Celia at dinner, where Colin McNaughton announced his engagement to her. Nigel claims he did not personally serve Celia coffee and denies involvement in her death or the theft of items from the house. When questioned about green ink found on Elizabeth Johnston's paper, Nigel suggests someone used his ink to frame him due to resentment among the residents, though he becomes evasive when pressed for details. Sharp considers whether Celia’s thefts were a psychological issue or a ploy to gain Colin's attention.\n\nSharp then questions Leonard Bateson, who admits to pouring coffee from a pot into a cup and placing it next to Celia, but denies adding morphine. Bateson claims he was distracted by an argument and did not see her drink the liquid. He becomes angry during the interrogation, insisting that Celia must have committed suicide. Sharp counters this by revealing that the suicide note was actually a fragment of a letter Celia had written earlier that morning, suggesting the note was a forgery.",
